# This repository + Waypost MCP

This git repo is the **Waypost application** source. When using Waypost MCP (`WAYPOST_API_TOKEN`), the token must come from the **same project in the app that tracks work for this codebase**—usually a project also named **Waypost** (or your canonical product project).

- **Wrong:** Reusing a Sync/API token from an unrelated project (e.g. another product). MCP will only list and mutate **that** project’s id; tasks and API calls will target the wrong place.
- **Right:** Open the **Waypost** project in the web app → **Sync** → copy the token (or download `waypost.json`) and set `WAYPOST_API_TOKEN` / merge MCP config. Use `project_id` from that file for `waypost_create_task`, `waypost_log_agent_phase`, etc.

**Profile (account) tokens** can see every project; still prefer naming clarity and passing the correct `project_id` when creating tasks so work lands on the Waypost product project.

If `waypost_list_projects` returns only one row, that is your scoped token’s project—confirm it matches the project you intend before creating tasks.

## Creating a new project and pointing this repo at it

When the user asks to create a **new** Waypost project and hook up **this** workspace:

1. Call **`waypost_create_project`** with **`issue_sync_token: true`** (plus `name`, optional `description` / `url`).
2. From the JSON response, write **`waypost_json`** verbatim to the repository root as **`waypost.json`** (that path should stay gitignored).
3. Set the editor MCP env **`WAYPOST_API_TOKEN`** to **`sync_token`**, or open **`cursor_mcp_install_url`** once to register MCP with the new token.
4. Do not commit `api_token` / secrets; remove `api_token` from `waypost.json` before any commit if the user adds it to tracked files by mistake.

Until step 3, MCP may still use the old token—remind the user to reload MCP or restart Cursor after updating env.
